<article>
    <h1>Edi&#xAD;ble gar&#xAD;den&#xAD;ing</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201220/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-20"><time>2020-12-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Chan&#xAD;tal Sa&#xAD;jan</span>
    </section>

    <p>Wel­come to the agri­hood.</p>
    <p>The re­cent buzz­word in ur­ban farm­ing cir­cles refers to neigh­bour­hoods that bond over a com­mon in­ter­est in grow­ing edi­ble pro­duce to­gether. It is a move­ment that is grad­u­ally tak­ing root here as more home farms sprout up in apart­ments, Hous­ing Board cor­ri­dors, com­mu­nity gar­den plots and rooftops.</p>
    <p>In 2005, the Na­tional Parks</p>
    <p>Board (NParks) launched the Com­mu­nity in Bloom (CIB) pro­gramme in Bukit Timah’s May­fair Park Es­tate. It sought to fos­ter a kam­pung spirit by bring­ing res­i­dents to­gether to help take Sin­ga­pore from a Gar­den City to a City in Na­ture.</p>
    <p>To­day, CIB has more than 1,600 com­mu­nity gar­dens is­land­wide, in­volv­ing more than 40,000 gar­den­ing en­thu­si­asts.</p>
    <p>The Covid-19 out­break re­sulted in sup­ply chain dis­rup­tions and a global rush to hoard food sup­plies, which raised the is­sue of food se­cu­rity. Sin­ga­pore, which cur­rently pro­duces less than 10 per cent of its nu­tri­tional needs lo­cally, as­pires to­wards a “30 by 30” goal – to pro­duce 30 per cent by 2030.</p>
    <p>In June, NParks l aunched its Gar­den­ing with Ed­i­bles ini­tia­tive to en­cour­age peo­ple to grow their own pro­duce at home. In to­tal, 400,000 seed pack­ets for leafy veg­eta­bles and fruit veg­eta­bles have been given out so far.</p>
    <p>NParks’ line-up of on­line edi­ble gar­den­ing work­shops has also stretched to May next year.</p>
    <p>Mr Bjorn Low, co-founder of ur­ban farm­ing social en­ter­prise Edi­ble Gar­den City, says: “We hope to ex­plore the health­care po­ten­tial of ur­ban farm­ing.</p>
    <p>“We will be work­ing with de­vel­op­ers, care in­sti­tu­tions and schools to not only build more edi­ble gar­dens and farms, but to also use th­ese spa­ces for spe­cialised gar­den­ing pro­grammes.”</p>

